To implement an observer pattern in Rust, we can use a combination of closures and references to achieve the desired behavior. Here's an example of how we can implement a simple observer pattern in Rust:
```json
// Define a struct to hold the observer and the function to call when the observable changes
struct Observer<T> {
  observer: &dyn FnMut(&T),
  value: T,
}

impl<T> Observer<T> {
  fn new(observer: &dyn FnMut(&T), value: T) -> Self {
    Self { observer, value }
  }
}

// Define a struct to hold the observable and the observers
struct Observable<T> {
  value: T,
  observers: Vec<Observer<T>>,
}

impl<T> Observable<T> {
  fn new(value: T) -> Self {
    Self { value, observers: Vec::new() }
  }

  fn add_observer(&mut self, observer: &dyn FnMut(&T)) {
    self.observers.push(Observer::new(observer, self.value));
  }

  fn remove_observer(&mut self, observer: &dyn FnMut(&T)) {
    self.observers.retain(|o| o.observer!= observer);
  }

  fn notify_observers(&mut self) {
    for observer in &mut self.observers {
      observer.observer(&self.value);
    }
  }
}

// Example usage
let mut observable = Observable::new(1);

let observer1 = &|&num: &i32| {
  println!("Observer 1: {}", num);
};

let observer2 = &|&num: &i32| {
  println!("Observer 2: {}", num);
};

observable.add_observer(observer1);
observable.add_observer(observer2);

observable.value = 2;

observable.notify_observers(); // Output: Observer 1: 2
                               // Output: Observer 2: 2
```
In this example, we define two structs: `Observer` and `Observable`. `Observer` holds a reference to a function that will be called when the observable changes, as well as the current value of the observable. `Observable` holds a vector of `Observer`s and provides methods for adding and removing observers, as well as notifying them of changes.

